Variable, typically mid- to dark brown throughout, recently emerged adults can be completely pale cream, head often darker than the rest of the body. A population in the Kilauea Iki caldera (form 
kilaueaiensis
) is typically yellow-orange or dark orange throughout, or occasionally with blue-green abdomens. Fore wing membrane slightly to noticeably fuscous.

Unpigmented to light brown, elongate ovoid, not sinusoidal, smooth, without striations, short pedicel 1/5 length from base, tail short to moderately long (Fig. 19
R-S
).

Makes pit galls on upper leaf surface. The leaf tissue often forms into a thickened rim of red or yellow around the immature (Fig. 46
L-P
). The Kilauea Iki population makes somewhat shallower pit galls on the upper leaf surface of low growing shrubs (~ 1m) in the bottom of the caldera. Eggs are laid individually or in small clusters long the upper leaf margin (Fig. 46K).
